with music and dancing. Douglas was the pyper, and the two favourite
airs of his majesty were "Kilt thy coat, Maggie, and come thy way with
me", and "Hulie the bed will fa'."'\[5\] Agnes Spark at Forfar (1661)
'did see about a dozen of people dancing, and they had sweet music
amongst them, and, as she thought, it was the music of a pipe'.\[6\]
Barton's wife was at a meeting in the Pentland Hills, where the Devil
'went before us in the likeness of a rough tanny Dog, playing on a pair
of Pipes. The

